{
  "What is the first step of the scientific method?": "",
  "Form a hypothesis about the topic": "",
  "Ask a question or make an observation": "",
  "Conduct the experiment right away": "",
  "Analyze the data you have collected": "",
  "The scientific method begins with an observation or question about the natural world. This curiosity drives the rest of the process — forming a hypothesis, testing it, and drawing conclusions.": "",
  "What is a hypothesis?": "",
  "A proven fact that has been confirmed through many experiments": "",
  "A testable prediction or educated guess based on observations": "",
  "The final conclusion written at the end of a lab report": "",
  "A summary of all the data collected during an experiment": "",
  "A hypothesis is a testable prediction about the outcome of an experiment, based on prior knowledge and observations. It is often written in an 'if...then...' format.": "",
  "What must a good hypothesis be?": "",
  "Proven correct before the experiment begins": "",
  "Testable through experiments or observations": "",
  "Based only on personal opinions and feelings": "",
  "Written after the experiment has been completed": "",
  "A good hypothesis must be testable — meaning it can be supported or refuted through experiments or observations. Statements based on opinions or beliefs that cannot be tested are not scientific hypotheses.": "",
  "After conducting an experiment, what should a scientist do with the data?": "",
  "Discard data that does not support the hypothesis": "",
  "Analyze the data and draw conclusions from it": "",
  "Change the data to match the expected results": "",
  "Repeat the experiment without looking at the data": "",
  "After an experiment, scientists analyze all data — whether or not it supports the hypothesis. Data analysis involves looking for patterns, calculating statistics, and determining if the hypothesis was supported.": "",
  "What happens if experimental data does not support the hypothesis?": "",
  "The experiment was a complete failure and has no value": "",
  "The scientist should revise the hypothesis and test again": "",
  "The data must be wrong and should be thrown out completely": "",
  "The scientist should change the data to support the hypothesis": "",
  "If data does not support the hypothesis, the experiment is still valuable. The scientist should revise the hypothesis based on what was learned and design a new experiment. Disproving a hypothesis is a valid scientific outcome.": "",
  "What is the purpose of the conclusion in the scientific method?": "",
  "To summarize whether the data supports or refutes the hypothesis": "",
  "To list all the materials that were used during the experiment": "",
  "To describe the step-by-step procedure of the experiment": "",
  "To create a new hypothesis for a completely different topic": "",
  "The conclusion summarizes the results and states whether the data supports or refutes the hypothesis. It may also include possible sources of error and suggestions for further investigation.": "",
  "Why is it important to share experimental results with other scientists?": "",
  "So others can verify the results by repeating the experiment": "",
  "So others cannot perform the same experiment themselves": "",
  "To prove that the scientist is smarter than other scientists": "",
  "It is not important; scientists should keep results private": "",
  "Sharing results allows other scientists to verify findings by repeating the experiment. This peer review process is essential for building confidence in scientific knowledge and catching errors.": "",
  "Which of the following is a properly written hypothesis?": "",
  "Plants are really interesting to study in experiments": "",
  "If plants receive more sunlight, then they will grow taller": "",
  "I think my experiment will work out very well this time": "",
  "Sunlight is the best thing for plants in every condition": "",
  "A proper hypothesis uses an 'if...then...' format and is testable. 'If plants receive more sunlight, then they will grow taller' clearly states the independent variable (sunlight) and the predicted outcome (taller growth).": "",
  "What is the correct order of the basic scientific method steps?": "",
  "Hypothesis, Question, Experiment, Conclusion, Analysis": "",
  "Question, Hypothesis, Experiment, Analysis, Conclusion": "",
  "Experiment, Question, Analysis, Hypothesis, Conclusion": "",
  "Conclusion, Experiment, Hypothesis, Question, Analysis": "",
  "The basic order is: (1) Ask a question, (2) Form a hypothesis, (3) Design and conduct an experiment, (4) Analyze data, (5) Draw a conclusion. This systematic approach helps ensure valid results.": "",
  "What does it mean to 'communicate results' in the scientific method?": "",
  "Sharing findings through reports, presentations, or published papers": "",
  "Keeping all data secret so no one else can use the findings": "",
  "Changing the data to make it more interesting for the audience": "",
  "Telling only the results that support the original hypothesis": "",
  "Communicating results means sharing all findings (including unexpected ones) through lab reports, scientific papers, or presentations. This transparency allows others to evaluate and build upon the research.": "",
  "What is the scientific method?": "",
  "A systematic process for investigating questions and solving problems in science": "",
  "A list of every scientific fact that has been discovered throughout all of history": "",
  "A single experiment that proves or disproves a theory once and for all time": "",
  "A set of strict rules that must be followed in the exact same order every time": "",
  "The scientific method is a systematic approach to investigating the natural world. While it follows general steps (observe, hypothesize, experiment, analyze, conclude), it is flexible and can be adapted to different situations.": "",
  "What is an observation in science?": "",
  "Using your senses or instruments to gather information about something": "",
  "A prediction about what will happen during a controlled experiment": "",
  "A mathematical calculation performed on collected experimental data": "",
  "A conclusion drawn after analyzing all data from multiple experiments": "",
  "An observation is information gathered by using your senses (sight, hearing, touch, smell) or scientific instruments (thermometers, balances). Observations can be qualitative (descriptive) or quantitative (numerical).": "",
  "What does 'inference' mean in the scientific method?": "",
  "A logical conclusion or interpretation based on observations and prior knowledge": "",
  "A direct measurement taken using a scientific instrument during a lab test": "",
  "A guess made without any evidence or observations to support the claim": "",
  "A step-by-step list of instructions for conducting a science experiment": "",
  "An inference is an interpretation or conclusion based on observations and reasoning. Unlike an observation (what you directly see), an inference involves explaining why something happened.": "",
  "What is a 'prediction' in the scientific method?": "",
  "A statement about what you expect will happen based on your hypothesis": "",
  "A final statement about what actually happened after the experiment ended": "",
  "A measurement taken during the experiment using laboratory instruments": "",
  "A description of the experimental procedure written before starting work": "",
  "A prediction is a specific, testable statement about what you expect to happen in an experiment based on your hypothesis. Predictions help guide what data to collect and how to design the experiment.": "",
  "What does 'peer review' mean in science?": "",
  "The process where other qualified scientists evaluate research before it is published": "",
  "A student reviewing notes with a classmate before taking a science test": "",
  "A teacher grading a student's completed lab report for a class assignment": "",
  "The process of conducting the same experiment a second time for accuracy": "",
  "Peer review is when other experts in the same field critically examine a scientist's methods, data, and conclusions before the work is published. This process helps catch errors and ensures quality.": "",
  "What is a 'conclusion' in the scientific method?": "",
  "A summary statement that explains whether the data supports or refutes the hypothesis": "",
  "The very first step taken before beginning any scientific investigation at all": "",
  "A list of materials and equipment needed to perform the experiment correctly": "",
  "The prediction about the expected outcome written before any testing begins": "",
  "A conclusion is the final step of the scientific method where the scientist summarizes findings, states whether the hypothesis was supported or refuted, discusses errors, and suggests future research.": "",
  "What does 'empirical evidence' mean?": "",
  "Information gathered through direct observation, measurement, or experimentation": "",
  "A belief or opinion about how the natural world works without any testing": "",
  "A prediction about the future based on personal feelings and intuitions": "",
  "Information copied from a textbook without performing any original research": "",
  "Empirical evidence is data collected through observation, measurement, or experimentation. It is the foundation of scientific knowledge — claims must be supported by empirical evidence to be accepted.": "",
  "What is a 'procedure' in the scientific method?": "",
  "The step-by-step instructions that describe how to carry out the experiment": "",
  "The final results and conclusions from the completed experiment analysis": "",
  "The hypothesis written before any experimental testing has been started": "",
  "The graph or data table created from the measurements that were taken": "",
  "A procedure is the detailed, step-by-step plan for conducting an experiment. A well-written procedure allows other scientists to repeat the experiment exactly, which is essential for reproducibility.": "",
  "What does 'testable question' mean?": "",
  "A question that can be investigated through experiments or observations": "",
  "A question that already has a well-known answer in every textbook": "",
  "A question based entirely on personal preferences or opinions only": "",
  "A question that requires no data collection to answer it correctly": "",
  "A testable question can be answered through experiments, observations, or data collection. 'Does fertilizer affect plant growth?' is testable, while 'Is blue the best color?' is not because it is based on opinion.": "",
  "What does 'replication' mean in the scientific method?": "",
  "Repeating an experiment to verify that the results are consistent and reliable": "",
  "Copying another scientist's hypothesis word for word without any changes": "",
  "Creating an identical copy of a living organism in a science laboratory": "",
  "Changing the independent variable between each trial of the experiment": "",
  "Replication means repeating an experiment under the same conditions to check if results are consistent. If multiple scientists get similar results, the findings are considered more reliable.": "",
  "A student notices that plants near the window grow taller than plants in the corner of the room. She wonders if light affects plant growth. What step of the scientific method is she performing?": "",
  "Forming a hypothesis about the outcome": "",
  "Making an observation and asking a question": "",
  "Analyzing the data from her experiment run": "",
  "Drawing a conclusion from collected evidence": "",
  "The student is at the first step — making an observation (plants near the window grow taller) and asking a question (does light affect growth?). This step sparks the rest of the scientific inquiry.": "",
  "A student hypothesizes that hot water dissolves sugar faster than cold water. She tests this by timing how long sugar takes to dissolve at different temperatures. After the experiment, her data shows hot water did dissolve sugar faster. What should she do next?": "",
  "Declare her hypothesis is proven as an absolute fact for all time": "",
  "Conclude that her data supports her hypothesis and repeat to verify": "",
  "Change her hypothesis to say cold water dissolves sugar faster instead": "",
  "Stop experimenting since one trial is enough to confirm any hypothesis": "",
  "She should conclude that her data supports the hypothesis, but one experiment does not 'prove' it. She should repeat the experiment to verify results and possibly share her findings for peer review.": "",
  "A student runs an experiment and gets results that contradict his hypothesis. He decides to throw away the data and only report results from trials that support his hypothesis. What is wrong with this approach?": "",
  "Nothing is wrong; scientists only need to report data that supports their claims": "",
  "This is scientific fraud because all data must be reported honestly and completely": "",
  "He should have thrown away the entire experiment and started a new topic": "",
  "This is acceptable as long as he tells the teacher about the discarded data": "",
  "Selectively reporting data is a form of scientific misconduct. All data must be reported honestly. Data that contradicts a hypothesis is valuable — it helps refine understanding and leads to better hypotheses.": "",
  "A scientist publishes a paper claiming a new medicine cures headaches. Other scientists try to repeat her experiment but cannot get the same results. What does this suggest?": "",
  "The original results are definitely correct and the other scientists made errors": "",
  "The original findings may not be reliable and further investigation is needed": "",
  "The experiment is too complicated for anyone else to repeat accurately": "",
  "All medicine research is unreliable and should not be trusted by anyone": "",
  "If other scientists cannot replicate results, the original findings may not be reliable. Reproducibility is a cornerstone of science. The original scientist may need to re-examine her methods or data.": "",
  "A student wants to know which paper towel brand absorbs the most water. Which is a testable hypothesis for this question?": "",
  "Paper towels are useful for cleaning up spills around the kitchen": "",
  "Brand X is the best paper towel because it has nice packaging": "",
  "If Brand X is thicker, then it will absorb more water than Brands Y and Z": "",
  "I personally prefer Brand Y because it feels softer when I use it": "",
  "The hypothesis 'If Brand X is thicker, then it will absorb more water' is testable because you can measure both thickness and water absorption. The other options are opinions or untestable statements.": "",
  "A student conducts an experiment on how exercise affects heart rate. She collects data and finds that her hypothesis was not supported. Her teacher says this is still a successful experiment. Why?": "",
  "Because the teacher is trying to make the student feel better about failing": "",
  "Because learning what does not work is still valuable scientific knowledge": "",
  "Because the student followed the procedure even though her data was wrong": "",
  "Because all experiments are considered successful regardless of the results": "",
  "An experiment is successful if it was conducted properly and produced valid data, regardless of whether the hypothesis was supported. Disproving a hypothesis provides valuable information that helps refine understanding.": "",
  "A group of students design an experiment but skip the background research step. They jump straight to testing. Why could this be a problem?": "",
  "It is not a problem because research only slows down the experimental process": "",
  "They may repeat mistakes others have made or miss important safety information": "",
  "Background research is only required for professional scientists in universities": "",
  "Skipping research makes the experiment more creative and produces better results": "",
  "Background research helps scientists understand what is already known, avoid repeating others' mistakes, identify safety hazards, and form better hypotheses. Skipping it can lead to flawed experiments.": "",
  "A student measures how far a ball travels when kicked with different amounts of force. She writes her conclusion as: 'My hypothesis was right because I wanted it to be.' What is wrong with this conclusion?": "",
  "Nothing is wrong because scientists should be confident about their predictions": "",
  "A conclusion must be based on data and evidence, not personal desires or wishes": "",
  "She should have simply stated her hypothesis was wrong to show good science": "",
  "A conclusion should only describe the materials used during the experiment": "",
  "Conclusions must be based on evidence from the data, not personal wishes. She should reference specific measurements from her experiment to explain whether or not the data supports her hypothesis.": "",
  "A scientist observes that ice cream sales and drowning incidents both increase in summer. She infers that ice cream causes drowning. What error in reasoning is she making?": "",
  "She is making a correct inference because the data clearly shows a direct cause": "",
  "She is confusing correlation with causation; both are caused by hot weather": "",
  "She should have collected more ice cream data before making any conclusions": "",
  "She is making a valid scientific hypothesis that should be tested further now": "",
  "She is confusing correlation (two things happening together) with causation (one thing causing the other). Hot weather causes both increased ice cream sales and more swimming, which leads to more drownings. Ice cream does not cause drowning.": "",
  "A student performs an experiment testing whether music volume affects concentration. She concludes that loud music reduces concentration. Her teacher asks what she should do next to strengthen her findings. What is the best answer?": "",
  "Publish the results immediately without any further testing needed": "",
  "Repeat the experiment with more participants and share results for peer review": "",
  "Change the hypothesis to match the results she already has on record": "",
  "Accept the conclusion as final since the experiment was done correctly once": "",
  "To strengthen findings, she should repeat the experiment with a larger sample size to increase reliability and share her results for peer review. One experiment with limited participants is not sufficient to draw firm conclusions.": ""
}